-- TAKE A LOOK-Banks' financial market trading desks feel the pinch
-- 
-- Thu Jun 12, 2014 02:31AM EDT
-- None



LONDON, June 11 (Reuters) - The boom years of financial market trading may be over - hit by a triple whammy of liquidity-sapping regulation, extraordinary monetary policies that have smothered the volatility traders rely on, and moves to lower margin electronic trading.

Revenues from fixed income, currencies and commodities, known as FICC, and from equity trading fell at many investment banks in the first quarter and, analysts say, may never regain pre-crisis peaks. Below is a selection of recent Reuters stories on the topic.   NEWS  >Stock trading's race for speed has run its course  [ID:nL5N0OT15N]  >No party for bankers despite bull market for shares[ID:nL6N0O85MD]  >Boom times for bank trading have gone, and may never come back [ID:nL5N0OQ24N]  >Lean times for investment banks put rates desks under fire [ID:nL5N0KX3U0]  >Volatility vaporised by "this time it's different"  [ID:nL6N0OD56] >Deutsche Bank to rein in global bond trading in profit push[ID:nL5N0KU142]  >Morgan Stanley bets on smaller bond unit, defying skeptics [ID:nL2N0KS00Z]  >Bond trading stings Goldman, Citi in 4th quarter   [ID:nL2N0KQ1SW]